Tantulocaridans are ectoparasitic crustaceans with a complex and incompletely known life cycle (

; 

; 

) that use a variety of other crustaceans, such as ostracods, copepods, isopods, tanaids, and amphipods, as their hosts (

; 

; 

). Currently, there are 39 described species belonging to 23 genera and five families (

; 

). The most speciose genera are 

Microdajus
Greve, 1965

and 

Tantulacus
Huys, Andersen and Kristensen, 1992

, with five species in each (

).The hosts for all described species in 

Microdajus

are tanaids whereas none of the hosts are known from any 

Tantulacus
species

as only free larvae have been collected, principally from meiofaunal samples. Tantulocaridans as a whole have been reported with a world-wide distribution (

) but only two species, 

Tantulacus coroniporus
Martinez Arbizu and Petrunina, 2017

and 

Aphotocentor kolbasovi
Petrunina and Huys, 2020

, have been described from the entire western Atlantic, specifically from the Argentinian abyssal plain (

) and the Campos Basin, 
Brazil
(

). In the present paper, we report the first species of tantulocaridan reported from the northwestern Atlantic, which is also the first tantulocaridan reported from the western Atlantic with a tanaid host.

